Sure — here's the same fix using CMake GUI and Windows Settings (no typing commands):
Step 1 — Check for extra protobuf using File Explorer
Open File Explorer, search your C: drive for a folder named protobuf
Common places to check: C:\vcpkg, C:\Program Files, C:\Program Files (x86)
If you find vcpkg installed, open it and see if protobuf is listed there
Step 2 — Remove protobuf from your PATH (if found)
Press Windows key, type "environment variables", open "Edit the system environment variables"
Click Environment Variables button
Under "System variables" (and "User variables"), find Path, select it, click Edit
Look through the list for anything mentioning protobuf or vcpkg — if found, select it and click Delete
Click OK on all windows to save
Step 3 — Delete your old build folder
Open File Explorer, go to C:\
Find the build_test folder
Right-click it → Delete
Right-click in C:\ → New → Folder, name it build_test again
Step 4 — Reconfigure using CMake GUI
Open CMake (cmake-gui) from Start Menu
In "Where is the source code" box, browse to select C:\opencv\sources
In "Where to build the binaries" box, browse to select C:\build_test
Click Configure
Choose your Visual Studio version (e.g. "Visual Studio 17 2022") and platform x64, click Finish
Once it loads the options list, use the search box at top and type each of these names, then uncheck the checkbox next to them:
WITH_GAPI
WITH_ADE
WITH_PROTOBUF
BUILD_PROTOBUF
OPENCV_DNN_ENABLE_PROTOBUF
Click Configure again
Click Generate
Step 5 — Build using Visual Studio
Click Open Project in CMake GUI (or open C:\build_test\OpenCV.sln manually)
Visual Studio will open
At the top, set build mode to Release
Right-click ALL_BUILD in Solution Explorer (right panel) → Build
That's it — this avoids the protobuf conflict entirely by turning off the parts that need it, which you don't use anyway.
